  7  I got burned by this once. It&#39;s a subtle difference but switching the function from arrow to data() {return {}} does the trick. Thanks mufasa.
    You can use an arrow function actually— the first argument will be a reference to the instance.  data: vm =&gt; ({ somevar: vm.messageId })
  @jvndev Yes, the two bottom ones are the same and the top one is an arrow function which handles the context differently
    To assign a data property equal to a props, you can use watcher, as following:
 &lt;script&gt; export default { props: [&#39;messageId&#39;], data: function(){ var theData={ somevar: &#34;&#34;, // other object attributes } }, watch: { messageId: function(newVal) { this.somevar = newVal } } }
  8  @RoyJ Yes, that also can be done, but If you want to update the data variable, than you have to use computed with getter.
  I mean you should replace the data item with a computed, if  somevar is never assigned by anything but the watcher.
  It makes the code clearer. A computed is effectively a watcher plus a data item.
      If you are rendering a  Child component, and want to set the  data variables by  props, you have to use both  this and  watch functions:
  &lt;script&gt;export default { data () { id: 0 }, props: [&#39;propId&#39;], methods: { init() { this.id = this.propId // step1. assign propId to id } }}&lt;/script&gt;
  &lt;script&gt;export default { data () { id: 0 }, props: [&#39;propId&#39;], methods: { init() { this.id = this.propId // step1. assign propId to id } }, // add this to your code , this is a MUST. // otherwise you won&#39;t SEE your data variable assigned by property watch { propId: function(new_value) { this.init() } }}&lt;/script&gt;
  Assuming you have two component:  Parent and  Child (  Child has a property naming as  propId ) , and  Child also have a &#34;async&#34; operation such as reading database.
